Issues.Body:
This PR fixes `theme(fontFamily.*)` output when the font family contains [`fontFeatureSettings` configuration](https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/pull/9039):

```js
/* Example config */
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    fontFamily: {
      sans: ['Inter', { fontFeatureSettings: '"cv11"' }],
    },
  },
}
```

```css
/* Input */
.example {
  font-family: theme('fontFamily.sans');
}

/* Output before fix */
.example {
  font-family: Inter, [object Object];
}

/* Output after fix */
.example {
  font-family: Inter;
}
```

I recently rebuild my whole module-packer pipeline because it seemed to fail purging tailwind classes..

Until I realised, that "w-fit" isn't contained in any .css file provided by the tailwindcss package.

Please add:

`.w-fit {
    width: fit-content;
}
`

to utilities.css

Previously only the following format was permitted:

```js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    fontFamily: {
      sans: ['Inter', 'sans-serif'],
    },
  },
}
```

Now all of these formats are permitted:

```js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    fontFamily: {
      sans: ['Inter', 'sans-serif'],
      sans2: [['Inter', 'sans-serif'], { fontFeatureSettings: '"cv11"' }],
      serif: 'Times, serif',
      serif2: ['Times, serif', { fontFeatureSettings: '"cv11"' }].
    },
  },
}
```

### References

- [`fontFamily` tests](https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/blob/master/tests/plugins/fontFamily.test.js)
- https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/pull/9039

**What version of Tailwind CSS are you using?**

3.1.8

**What build tool (or framework if it abstracts the build tool) are you using?**

Vite@2.9.14, postcss@8.4.14

**What version of Node.js are you using?**

v16.16.0

**What browser are you using?**

Chrome 104

**What operating system are you using?**

macOS

**Reproduction URL**

https://play.tailwindcss.com/UDRYIpLn4a?file=css

**Describe your issue**

In tailwind.config I've set the settings:
```js
  {
    container: {
      center: true,
      padding: {
        DEFAULT: '2rem',
        md: '1.5rem',
        xl: '1rem',
      },
    },
  },
```

But unfortunately for `2xl:container` all of the paddings are being generated inside double nested media query:
```css
@media (min-width: 1536px) {
  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .\32xl\:container {
      max-width: 640px;
    }
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .\32xl\:container {
      max-width: 768px;
      padding-right: 1.5rem;
      padding-left: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
  
  /* etc */
}
```

Which makes paddings applied effectively unusable when using breakpoint variants :(

I would expect that padding declarations would be only in a single media queries, like:
```css
  .\32xl\:container {
      padding-right: 1rem;
      padding-left: 1rem;
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .\32xl\:container {
      padding-right: 1.5rem;
      padding-left: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
```

Hello,

This PR adds h-stretch, min-h-stretch, max-h-stretch, w-stretch, min-w-stretch, and max-w-stretch utilities.

The autoprefixer will take care of vendor prefixing and will generate the following CSS:
```css
height: -webkit-fill-available;
height: -moz-available;
height: stretch;
```

Thanks,
Otto
